The manifest loads fine, then DPUL follows the seeAlso to get the jsonld, which returns a 406 "Not Acceptible" here: https://github.com/pulibrary/dpul/blob/6dce643808098684c6ce3dbb91ec896b5d1299e5/app/values/manifest_metadata.rb

However, there doesn't appear to be an issue with Accept headers or anything, because a browser loads it fine in a logged-in window but gets the 406 in an incognito window.

It seems like we need to handle authorization of jsonld show pages the same way we handle authorization of manifests. i.e. if `can :manifest` then you should be able to see the jsonld.
Or maybe jsonld should show if `can :discover`

comments.body: Closed by #3392

The ruby interpreter will install a specific bundler version. In order to change this you need to change the ruby version and use a different bundler version. 
Locally when I want to use a different bundler version to bundle the gems:
1. I install the bundler version I want and then I run `bundle _theversionnumber_ install`
2. If the previous installed version is marked as default step 1 will not work. Then I need to look in the `specifications/default` directory and remove it from there. 
3. `gem env` provides the installation path which is `INSTALLATION DIRECTORY: /usr/local/lib/ruby/gems/3.1.0` . You can check what is installed as default in `/usr/local/lib/ruby/gems/{ruby_version}/specifications/default/`. In the bibdata-alma-staging case it indicates that bundler default is `bundler-2.3.25.gemspec`. In order to change the default : 
4.  i) `rm  /usr/local/lib/ruby/gems/{ruby_version}/specifications/default/bundler-2.3.25.gemspec` , ii) reinstall the desired ruby version as default (needs a default flag --default) ,  iii) uninstall the previous installed version.  
This needs to be well tested as there might be more than one bundler defaults in the default directory.
this work was already done by another PR.
